s at a time when governments of most newly independent countries were busy trying to promote heavy industry by protectionist trade policies and import-substituting industrialization. The purpose of this book is two-fold. It is intended to introduce a host of energy-related discussions relevant to a wider group of readers who do not “do energy” for a living, yet are keenly interested in understanding the many complexities of modern industrial societies which need to balance economic, environmental, and security priorities of ordinary citizens. It is also meant to serve as an introductory assessment of key energy-related issues, with a particular relevance for small advanced countries such as Singapore.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEnergy developmentxEnvironmental aspectszSingapore. 0aEnergy development. 0aEnergy policyzSingapore. 0aEnergy policy. 0aPower resourcesxEconomic aspectszSingapore. 0aPower resources. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Energy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066300608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017z978311060667640uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981462067340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814620673423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789814620673.jpg  a978-3-11-060667-6  ISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017c2015d2017  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  a978-3-11-066300-6  ISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  a